						<summary>

						<p><hi rend="bold">Ballāḷa. III: A.D. 1310.</hi></p>						

						<p>The beginning of the inscription is lost. It refers to a perpetual gift of land measuring 300 <hi rend="italic">kuli</hi>, situated close to a tank, to the temple of Muḷnāchchi by Dāsaya Nāyaka, son of Agattiyāṇḍi Nāyakkar, who was the Commander <hi rend="italic">(sēṉāpati)</hi> of the <hi rend="italic">Valaṅgai</hi> regiment. The tank was excavated by one Kaṇḍar, a member of Vīrachōḻa Aṇukkar and the son of Ālakkāmīṇḍāṉ. The three symbols, drum, dagger and an anvil are engraved at the bottom of the record.</p>						

						<p>Published in <hi rend="italic">E.C.</hi> (n), Vol. IV, No. Kol. 113.</p>						

						</summary>
